5","about 1346":"about 1346","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","about 1375":"about 1375","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Water","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegfried, Wolf.","English: variant of   Walter  , a common medieval pronunciation of which was <i>Water</i>.","English and German (Rhineland): topographic name for someone who lived by a stretch of water, Middle English and Low German <i>water</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Wetter","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of numerous places so named.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wēt(t)er</i> ‘weather, thunderstorm’ for an irritable person.","German: nickname for someone who liked to wager, from Middle High German <i>wetten</i> ‘to bet, wager’."]},{"name":"Watterson","meanings":["English and Scottish: patronymic meaning ‘son of   Water   1’, a short form of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Waterman","meanings":["English and Dutch: occupational name for a boatman or ferryman, or a water carrier (the English name was perhaps sometimes synonymous with Middle English <i>waterlader</i> or <i>waterberer</i>, denoting a man who carried fresh water from a spring or stream for drinking or domestic use), or a topographic name for someone who lived by a pond or stretch of water (see   Water   2).","English: occupational name from the Middle English personal name   Water   or   Walter   + <i>man</i>, meaning ‘servant of <i>Wa(l)ter</i>’.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Wassermann   or Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Wasserman  ."]},{"name":"Warter","meanings":["English: habitational name from Warter (in East Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>wearg</i> ‘felon, criminal’ + <i>trēow</i> ‘tree’, i.e. a gallows. There has been some confusion with   Water  .","German (Bavaria): unexplained."]},{"name":"Waters","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Water   1 and 2, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: when not the English surname, this is an Anglicized form of various Gaelic names taken to be derived from <i>uisce</i> ‘water’ (see for example   Haskin  ,   Hiskey  ).","History: James Waters came from London, England, to Salem, MA, in 1630. Lawrence Waters came to Charlestown, MA, from Lancaster, England, in 1675."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Water was born about 1346, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Symon de Water, was 28 and his mother, de Water, was 28. He married de Water about 1375, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1346–":"umbes 1346–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1345":"umbes 1345","about 1346":"umbes 1346","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","about 1375":"umbes 1375","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1346–":"noin 1346–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1345":"noin 1345","about 1346":"noin 1346","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","about 1375":"noin 1375","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1346–":"environ 1346–Décédé","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1346":"1346","1320":"1320","about 1345":"environ 1345","about 1346